# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] General elections were held in Sweden in 1866.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] They were the first elections for the new Second Chamber (*Andra kammaren*) in the Riksdag, which would serve a three-year term.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] Suffrage was given to men over the age of 21 who either had a taxable income of at least 800 riksdaler a year, owned a property worth at least 1,000 riksdaler, or rented a property taxed to at least 6,000 riksdaler.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] This meant that around 5.5% of the population were able to vote, a slight reduction from the 6% that had been eligible under the previous Estates system.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] The changes had been approved following a 60,000-strong petition and a vote in the House of Nobility in December 1865 during which crowds had gathered outside to pressure the nobles into approving it.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] The 190 seats consisted of one representative from every Domsaga (or two for Domsaga with a population exceeding 40,000) and one representative for every 10,000 residents of a town (with smaller towns merged into combined constituencies).
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] Candidates were required to be at least 25 years old.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] Around 187,000 voters qualified by real estate, 9,500 through their rental arrangements and 10,500 through their income.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] Many property owners were farmers, giving the rural Lantmanna Party a dominant position in the second chamber.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] The other house in the Riksdag, the 125-seat First Chamber, was dominated by the upper classes, with membership restricted to the 6,000 wealthiest people in the country, less than 1% of the population.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1866-swedish-general-election] Of the 190 elected members, 107 had previously served in the Estates.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1869-swedish-general-election] General elections were held in Sweden in 1869 to elect the Second Chamber of the Riksdag for a three-year term.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1869-swedish-general-election] In urban areas the elections were direct, whilst in some rural areas the vote was indirect, using electors.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1869-swedish-general-election] The Second Chamber had one representative from every Domsaga (or two for Domsaga with a population over 40,000) and one representative for every 10,000 residents of a town (with smaller towns merged into combined constituencies).
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1872-swedish-general-election] General elections were held in Sweden in 1872 to elect the Second Chamber of the Riksdag for a three-year term.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1872-swedish-general-election] Following the elections, the Lantmanna Party was the largest party, holding 90 of the 194 seats.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1872-swedish-general-election] Of a total population of 4.2 million, only 236,120 people (6%) were eligible to vote.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1872-swedish-general-election] Direct elections were held in 22 of the 24 urban constituencies and 60 of the 138 rural constituencies.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1872-swedish-general-election] In the other 80 constituencies, the elections were indirect and carried out using electors.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1875-swedish-general-election] General elections were held in Sweden in 1875 to elect the Second Chamber of the Riksdag for a three-year term.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1875-swedish-general-election] Following the elections, the Lantmanna Party remained the largest party, holding 92 of the 198 seats.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1875-swedish-general-election] Suffrage was given to men over the age of 21 who either had a taxable income of at least 800 krona a year, owned a property worth at least 1,000 krona, or rented a property taxed to at least 6,000 krona.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1875-swedish-general-election] Of a total population of 4.4 million, only 255,552 people (6%) were eligible to vote.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1875-swedish-general-election] Direct elections were held in 23 of the 24 urban constituencies and 67 of the 138 rural constituencies, an increase of eight constituencies using direct elections.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1875-swedish-general-election] In the other 72 constituencies, the elections were indirect and carried out using electors.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1878-swedish-general-election] General elections were held in Sweden in 1878 to elect the Second Chamber of the Riksdag for a three-year term.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1878-swedish-general-election] Following the elections, the Lantmanna Party remained the largest party, holding 92 of the 204 seats.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1878-swedish-general-election] Direct elections were held in 21 of the 24 urban constituencies and 73 of the 140 rural constituencies, an increase of four constituencies using direct elections.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1878-swedish-general-election] In the other 70 constituencies, the elections were indirect and carried out using electors.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1878-swedish-general-election] Of a total population of 4.5 million, only 270,337 people (6%) were eligible to vote.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1881-swedish-general-election] General elections were held in Sweden in 1881 to elect the Second Chamber of the Riksdag for a three-year term.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1881-swedish-general-election] Following the elections, the Lantmanna Party remained the largest party, holding 101 of the 206 seats.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1881-swedish-general-election] Direct elections were held in all 24 urban constituencies and 78 of the 142 rural constituencies, an increase of six constituencies using direct elections.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1881-swedish-general-election] In the other 64 rural constituencies, the elections were indirect and carried out using electors.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1881-swedish-general-election] Of a total population of 4.6 million, only 281,193 people (6%) were eligible to vote.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1890-swedish-general-election] General elections were held in Sweden in 1890.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1890-swedish-general-election] Pro-free trade candidates received a majority of the vote.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1890-swedish-general-election] Gustaf Åkerhielm remained Prime Minister.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1890-swedish-general-election] The Free Traders and the new Swedish Social Democratic Party ran joint lists in some constituencies.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1890-swedish-general-election] Only 23% of the male population aged over 21 was eligible to vote.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden] The **1995 European Parliament election in Sweden** was the election of Members of the European Parliament representing the Sweden constituency for the 1995–1999 term of the European Parliament.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden] Austria, Finland and Sweden acceded to the Union on 1 January 1995.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden] 59 delegates (21 from Austria, 16 from Finland, 22 from Sweden) were appointed to the Parliament on accession, bringing the total up to 626.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden] Elections to elect the 22 MEPs for Sweden were held on 17 September 1995 and the now-elected MEPs took their seats with effect from 9 October 1995.
[src:1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden/1995-european-parliament-election-in-sweden] The Swedish Social Democratic Party won these elections, They have won every European parliament election since, as of 2024.
